<section xml:id="syllabus" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Syllabus</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      Welcome to Molecular Biology! 
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <!-- Include chapters -->
  <subsection xml:id="sec-course-info">
    <title>Course Information</title>

    <p>
      This is the syllabus for <term>BIOL 262 Molecular Biology</term> for Fall 2026
      It is a 1.25 credit course.
      <!-- use a description list (dl) for short items -->
      <dl>
        <li>
          <title>Instructor</title>

          <p>
            Professor Rachel Avard
          </p>
          <p>  
          Hemenway Annex 614
          </p>
          <p>
          978-566-9009 
          </p> 
          <p>
            <url href="mailto:prof.lastname@example.edu">ravard@framingham.edu</url>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Office Hours</title>

          <p>
            Walk ins are welcome! Students who make appointments will have priority, but if I am in my office and I’m not meeting with anyone else, please feel free to stop by with any questions you have. I am here to help! In most situations, students are limited to 30 minutes of office hours a week. This is to ensure that all students have fair access to office hours, as well as to ensure that each student has the opportunity to work through material independently. This rule can be broken in appropriate / extenuating situations, please speak with me if the need arises! 
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Monday</em> 12:30 - 1:30 pm
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Tuesday</em> 11:00 - 12:00
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Friday</em> 1:30 - 2:30 
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Lecture Times</title>

          <p>
            MWRF 11:30 - 12:20 pm
          </p>
        </li>

         <li>
          <title>Lecture Location</title>

          <p>
            Hemenway Hall 110
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Course Description</title>

          <p>
            An examination of the way the cell accesses, uses, and maintains the information stored in the genome. It begins with an overview of DNA structure and topology, continues with replication, transcription, and translation, and concludes with gene regulation. Special topics could include cancer, stem cells, and RNAi, and focusing on the structure-function relationships of the molecules involved in these processes. Students are required to enroll in the corresponding laboratory (3 hours). Corequisite: BIOL 262L Molecular Biology Lab Prerequisites: BIOL 135 Foundations of Biological Science with Lab, and CHEM 108 Principles of Chemistry and Quantitative Analysis with Lab; or permission of the instructor
1.250 Credit hours
4.000 Lecture hours
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Learning Objectives</title>

          <p>
            1.	<em>Remember</em> the names and functions of biomolecules involved in the Central Dogma of Biology
            </p>
            <p>
            2.	<em>Understand</em> how each of those molecules accomplish their goal
            </p>
            <p>
            3.	<em>Apply</em> this your knowledge of these molecules to how other related molecules work
           </p>
            <p>
            4.	<em>Analyze</em> molecular mechanisms and describe why each molecule is vital to the process 
            </p> 
            <p>
            5.	<em>Evaluate</em> how effective molecular mechanisms are and hypothesize why they function this way evolutionarily
            </p>
            <p>
            6.	<em>Create</em> new experiments and presentations based on the knowledge obtained in this course
          </p>
        </li>
       
        <li>
          <title>Textbook</title>

          <p>
            <pubtitle>Molecular Biology of the Gene, 7th Ed.</pubtitle>
            by Watson et. al
          </p>
        </li>
      </dl>
    </p>






  <!-- Use paragraphs to break apart subsections -->
    <paragraphs>
      <title>Course And University Policies</title>

      <p>
        <dl>
        <li>
          <title>Attendance In Lecture</title>

          <p>
            Attendance to each lecture session is required
          </p>
          <p>
            I know life happens, so there is no grade penalty for missing a lecture
         </p>
          <p>
 	          You are responsible for everything that comes out of my mouth regardless of if you come to lecture or not
          </p>
          <p>
 	          Please note that missing a lecture does not permit work to be turned in late 
          </p>
          <p>
            If you need an extension, you must receive permission from me ASAP (see below)
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Attendance in Lab</title>

          <p>
            Attendance in lab is mandatory. For safety reasons, labs cannot be made up
          </p>
          <p>
 	          Students who miss a lab session will receive a 0% for that week’s lab (excluding extenuating circumstances)
          </p>
          <p>
            Missing <em>two labs</em> will automatically result in failing the course
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Extensions, Missing Work, and Makeup Policies</title>

          <p>
            Should you need an extension, please speak with me ASAP. Students will be accommodated to the maximum extent of my ability, but only if you speak to me as far in advance as possible.
          </p>
          <p>
            Extensions cannot be granted on or following the due date (except in extreme extenuating circumstances) 
            </p>
          <p>
            All late work will receive a 10% deduction per day that it is late, not to exceed 20%.
          </p>
          <p>
            All homework is due before the exam that covers the same material as that homework with no exceptions excluding extenuating circumstances (speak with Dr. Avard ASAP)
          </p>
          <p>
            All creative study guides have a final deadline of the day before the respective exam at 11:30am, and will not be accepted after this time.
          </p>
          <p>
            The 3MT cannot be submitted late.
 	        </p>
          <p>
            All assignments are due at the beginning of the class period (11:30 for lecture, 1:30 for Lab)
          </p>
          <p>
            Any assignments submitted later than the beginning of the class period will receive a late penalty.
 	        </p>
          <p>
            There will be no makeup exams with the exception of extreme extenuating circumstance
          </p>
        </li>

         <li>
          <title>Course Credit Hour Statement</title>

          <p>
            This course meets weekly for a total of 4 hours lecture and 3 hours of lab and is worth 4 credit hours.  Most of the work done to successfully complete this course will be executed outside of class time. For each hour of lecture time, students are expected to work a <em>minimum of two hours</em> outside of class on assigned problems, assignments, reading, and studying for this course.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Accommodation Statement for Students with Disabilities</title>

          <p>
            Framingham State University offers equal opportunities to all qualified students, including those with disabilities. The University is committed to making reasonable accommodations as necessary to ensure that its programs and activities do not discriminate, or have the effect of discriminating, on the basis of disability. Disability/Access Services works with students with ADD/ADHD, Autism Spectrum Disorder, learning and psychiatric disabilities, students with mobility disabilities, students who are blind or low vision, students who are d/Deaf or hard of hearing, and students with chronic medical conditions.
          </p> 
          <p>     
            Disability/Access Services works to provide reasonable accommodations to qualified students. The purpose of accommodations, and/or auxiliary aids is to reduce or eliminate any barriers that may exist because of a disability. Framingham State University is not mandated by law to waive specific courses or academic requirements considered essential to a particular program or degree. Rather, the University is mandated to ensure access so that individuals are not discriminated against on the basis of their disability.​
          </p>
          <p>
           <url href="mailto:disabilityservices@example.edu">disabilityservices@framingham.edu</url>. 
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Framingham State University Academic Honesty Policy</title>

          <p>
          Integrity is essential to academic life. Consequently, students who enroll at Framingham State University agree to maintain high standards of academic honesty and scholarly practice. They shall be responsible for familiarizing themselves with the published university policies and procedures regarding academic honesty. Faculty members are required to reference the university policy on academic honesty in their syllabi, and they shall, at their discretion, include in their course syllabi additional statements on definitions of academic honesty and academic honesty policies specific to their courses if applicable.
          </p>

          <p>
          <em>Infractions of the Policy on Academic Honesty include, but are not limited to:</em>
          </p>
          <p>
            Plagiarism: claiming as one’s own work the published or unpublished literal or paraphrased work of another;
          </p>
          <p>
            1. Cheating on exams, tests, quizzes, assignments, and papers, including the distribution or acceptance of these materials and other sources of information without the permission of the instructor(s);
          </p>
          <p>
            2. Unauthorized collaboration with other individuals in the preparation of course assignments;
          </p>
          <p>
            3. Submitting without authorization the same assignment for credit in more than one course;
          </p>
          <p>
            4. Use of dishonest procedures in computer, laboratory, studio, or field work;
           </p>
          <p>
           5. Misuse of the University’s technical and educational facilities either maliciously or for personal gain;
          </p>
          <p>
           6. Falsification of forms used to document the academic record and to conduct the academic business of the University.
          </p>
          <p>
           7. The enlistment of another individual or entity to complete one’s course work.
          </p>
          <p>
            For more information regarding the FSU Academic Honesty Policy, please reference the FSU Student Handbook 
          </p>
        </li>
       
        <li>
          <title>FSU Antiracism Policy</title>

          <p>
            At Framingham State University, faculty, staff, and students work together to sustain a learning, working, and living community free from hate, discrimination, harassment, and intolerance. We recognize the damaging effects of systemic racism—including policies, structures, and historic practices—on the experience and success of communities of color. Coming from different backgrounds and different levels of privilege, we can all affirm and engage in antiracist work.
          </p>
          <p>
            Diversity of voices, and of minds, strengthens our ability to solve problems and to ask and answer questions about the world we share. As your instructor, I commit to upholding community values of inclusion, civility, accessibility, and mutual respect. I expect this class to commit to creating a community that affirms and welcomes all persons from diverse backgrounds and experiences, and supports the realization of everyone’s potential.
          </p>
        </li>

         <li>
          <title>Technology Policy</title>

          <p>
            Students will need access to an up to date laptop in order to accomplish course work and lab reports, and will need to regularly check canvas and their school email accounts.
          </p>
          <p>
            Laptops, tablets, etc. are welcome in class as learning tools.
          </p>
          <p>
            Please refrain from use of technology that will be distracting to you or your classmates.
          </p>
        </li>
        
        <li>
          <title>Artificial Intelligence Policy</title>

          <p>
            In my opinion, AI is an incredible tool that has immense power, but can also cause a lot of damage and inaccuracies when used incorrectly
          </p>
          <p>
            You may (and will even be required to at times!) use AI in this class, but you may not use AI to generate any content that you submit as your own work.
          </p>
          <p>
            You <em>MAY</em> use AI for: proof reading, thought partner, explaining complex concepts, gathering literature resources, creating practice problems to work through content, explaining how to use new software, etc.
          </p>
          <p>
            You <em>MAY NOT</em> use AI for: answering problem set questions, answering exam questions, creating creative study guides, writing lab reports, etc
          </p>
          <p>
            AI <em>MAY NOT</em> be used to fully or even partially generate any content that you submit to be graded in this course 
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>US Copyright Law</title>

          <p>
            Please click here to find the US TEACH Act, which prohibits students from saving, distributing, or altering course content without permission
          </p>
       </li>

      </dl>
      </p>
    </paragraphs>
  </subsection>

  

  <!-- Other subsections for larger dividers -->
  <subsection xml:id="sec-assessments">
    <paragraphs>
      <title>Assignments and Grades</title>
      <p>
        <dl>
        <li>
          <title>Assignment Weight</title>
          <p>
              Exams - 30%
            </p>
            <p>
              Laboratory - 30%
            </p>
            <p>
              Final Exam (Cumulative) - 10%
            </p>
            <p>
              Problem Sets - 10%
            </p>
            <p>
              Creative Study Guides - 10%
            </p>
            <p>
              Structure Quiz - 5%
            </p>
            <p>
              3 Minute Thesis - 5%
            </p>
            <p>
                   
            </p>
            <p>
              Participation Up to 2 extra credit points 
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <title>Letter Grade Assignmets</title>
          <p>
              A 95 - 100
          </p>
          <p>
              A- 90 - 94.99
          </p>
          <p>
              B+ 87 - 89.99
          </p>
          <p>
              B 83 - 86.99
          </p>
          <p>
              B- 80 - 82.99
          </p>
          <p>
              C+ 77 - 79.99
          </p>
          <p>
              C 73 - 76.99
          </p>
          <p>
              C- 70 - 72.99
          </p>
          <p>
              D+ 67 - 69.99
          </p>
          <p>
              D 63 - 66.99
          </p>
          <p>
              D- 60 - 62.99
          </p>
          <p>
              D 0 - 59.99
          </p>
       </li>

       <li>
          <title>Important Grading Notes </title>
          <p>
               	Please note that you must have a <em>passing grade</em> in both <em>the lab and the lecture</em> in order to pass this course
          </p>
          <p>
               	The goal of this grading scheme is to show your overall mastery of material in this course. Therefore, if your <em>final exam score is higher</em> than any of your first 3 exam scores, I will <em>drop your lowest exam</em> score and replace that score with your final exam score. 
          </p>
          <p>
               	There will be no class scale (I do not believe that your grade should depend on the grade of your classmates)
          </p>
          <p>
                However, if the entire class does poorly on an assignment, that is a reflection on how the material was taught or on the quality of the assessment tool
          </p>
          <p>
                Should the entire class do poorly on an assignment, we will discuss together the plan moving forward to ensure that all students are able to learn the material and demonstrate their understanding in an appropriate way
          </p> 
          <p>
              <em>Important Note</em> nothing submitted in this course can be generated in part or full by other people, online resources, AI, or by any entity other than yourself! Breaking this rule will result in an automatic 0% on the assignment and being reported to Academic Affairs. 
          </p>         
       </li>

       <li>
          <title>Exams</title>
          <p>
              The purpose of this course is to truly understand the science behind molecular biology, and to begin honing your skills to think critically and communicate effectively as scientists
          </p>
          <p>
              Exams will be comprised of:
          </p>
          <p>
              Short Answer Questions
          </p>
          <p>
              Essay Questions 
          </p>
          <p>
              Pictographic questions that ask students to complete tables, Venn Diagrams, label images, sketch diagrams etc.
          </p>
          <p>
              Exam questions will pull from multiple chapters and sections and ask you to pull information together to create a cohesive answer. <em>Anything covered in lecture, in lab, or in the assigned problem sets</em> is fair game on the exams. 
          </p>
          <p>
              The best way to prepare for exams will be to regularly go through your class notes, complete the problem sets, and use the provided creative study guides
          </p>
          <p>
              Exam style: students will have the option to take the semester exams either <em>written or orally</em>
          </p>
          <p>
              The content will be identical, this is simply a way to allow students to demonstrate their knowledge in a format that will work best for them!
          </p>
          <p>
              If you opt to take the exam orally, you must schedule with me at least <em>1 week</em> prior to the exam date. 
          </p>
          <p>
              There will be a written, <em>cumulative final exam</em> at the end of the semester that will cover all material taught during the course of the semester
          </p>
       </li>

       <li>
          <title>Structure Quiz</title>
          <p>
              In molecular biology, we will be talking extensively about the structure – function relationships of biological molecules. In order to be able to have these in-depth conversations, we need to all know the structures of the fundamental building blocks of nucleic acids and proteins. As such, we will have a quiz on which you will be tested on the:
          </p>
          <p>
              Names and abbreviations of all amino acids and nucleic acids
          </p>
          <p>
              Structures of all amino acids (the full structures and the R groups)
          </p>
          <p>
             	Structures of all nucleotides (including all phosphate, sugar, and base components)
          </p>
          <p>
              This quiz will include: 
          </p>
          <p>
             	Drawing structures of amino acids and nucleic acids
          </p>
          <p>
             	Labeling amino acids and nucleic acids
          </p>
          <p>
             	Using any abbreviations for these structures that is requested. 
          </p>
       </li>

       <li>
          <title>Laboratory Assignments</title>
          <p>
              Laboratory assignments will include labs, lab reports, lab notebook quizzes, lab packets, etc. See lab syllabus for details.
          </p>
       </li>

       <li>
          <title>Problem Sets</title>
          <p>
              The best way to learn the information in this course is to apply it to the problem sets assigned. Problem sets are due every Thursday, and will be posted to Canvas by midnight every Thursday.
          </p>
          <p>
             	Problem sets are due every <em>Thursday</em>
          </p>
          <p>
             	All problem sets have a <em>final due date</em> of the day before exams
          </p>
          <p>
              Problem sets will not receive any late points if submitted up until the day before the exam
          </p>
          <p>
              Absolutely <em>no problem sets will be accepted</em> after 11:30 the day before each exam!
          </p>
          <p>
             	Problem set answer keys will be posted to Canvas the day before each exam
          </p>
          <p>
              You can <em>request problem set answer keys</em> at any point after you have submitted that problem set
          </p>
          <p>
              Problem sets are meant to test both your memory and understanding or course content, as well as to test your ability to comprehend, apply, design, and approach complex problems. Problem sets will frequently contain questions that we won’t have covered directly in class, but that we will have worked on all necessary tools needed to answer these questions. 
          </p>
          <p>
              The goal of the problem sets is to test your full understanding of the material. As such, your target audience is <em>NOT me</em>! Your answers should be written in a way that one of your peers could understand the topic that you are discussing.  Problem sets must be written in complete sentences and be linear.
          </p>
          <p>
              If your handwriting is messy or difficult to read, please type your problem sets. Problem sets with copious side notes, scribbles, and notes in the margins will not be accepted. 
          </p>
          <p>
              Problem sets are graded as ++ (100%), + (90%),  (80%), -(70%), -- (50%), or 0%. Problem sets will be graded both on correctness as well as on effort.
          </p>
          <p>
              Students will lose points for things including but not limited to: incorrect answers, incomplete answers, answers that fail to explain, answers that provide only 1 - 2 sentences when a full paragraph was expected, answers that do not use sketches when asked, answers that only use sketches and lack explanations, and answers that repeatedly make the same mistake that students have already received feedback for and have failed to address.
          </p>
          <p>
              Each question will receive a score of **** (Answered Well), *** (Answered but with minor details missing or slight inaccuracies), ** (Answered but with several details missing or several  inaccuracies), *(Answered with many details missing or many inaccuracies), or 0 (not answered or answered so poorly that the answer receives no credit.
          </p>
          <p>
              Problem sets must be submitted on the document posted to Canvas, and you <em>may NOT alter that document</em> (i.e. you may not give yourself additional space to answer certain questions). 
          </p>
          <p>
              Documents that have been altered in any way will not be graded 
          </p>
          <p>
             	Problem Set Formatting
          </p>
          <p>
              Problem sets must be <em>neat and legible</em>, otherwise they will not be graded.
          </p>
          <p>
              If you are concerned that your handwriting is not legible, please type your problem sets
          </p>
          <p>
              Problem sets written in pen with copious scribbles <em>will not be graded</em>. Please use a pencil, an erasable pen, or neatly use white out to remove 
          </p>
          <p>
              All problem sets must be submitted  in <em>pencil or in black ink</em>.
          </p>
          <p>
              Problem sets may not be submitted in font that is smaller than 11 pt font
          </p>
          <p>
              Any problem set that is not easily understandable / legible for any reason will not be graded.
          </p>
          <p>
              You may, and in fact, it's suggested that you walk through these problem sets with your peers. However, <em>all students must turn in their own, completely unique answers to the assigned problems</em>. Students caught turning in problem set answers that are identical or very similar to their classmates or to sources online <em>will receive a 0% for the assignment</em> and be reported to Academic Affairs
          </p>
          <p>
              Any answers on problem sets or exams that cover content that was not covered in this class will result in no credit for that question, and may result in being reported to Academic Affairs (see above for Academic Honesty Policy)
          </p>
       </li>

       <li>
          <title>Creative Study Guides</title>
          <p>
            This is a creative assignment that is meant to be fun, aid you in your studying, help improve your grade, and, most importantly, enhance your comprehension of the course material. A study guide is due the Monday prior to each of the 3 in class exams. The material and style are entirely up to you. 
          </p>
          <p>
            Study guides <em>must cover all material</em> that will be covered on that exam
          </p>
          <p>
            Study guides can be in any format that you'd like, including: written guides of the material covered in the exam, a rap song, a lesson plan, a mock interview / radio station story / breaking news report, a poem, a set of written questions that you think may be on the exam (must include at least 20 well-conceived questions with a separate document containing well worded answers. Questions should be reminiscent of questions I ask on psets), etc
          </p>
          <p>
            If you have an idea for a study guide but are not sure if it is appropriate, come chat with me
          </p>
          <p>
            Students may NOT submit study guides that contain words, pictures, questions, screenshots, etc. of any of the material that I have presented for this course (including but not limited to: psets, lecture slides, pictures of drawings I did on the board, lab documents, etc.).
          </p>
          <p>
            I will review study guides on the day of submission, and then study guides will be released to the class (with your name and any identifying markers removed when possible [if you chose to do a film/song/interview etc. I may not be able to remove identifying markers for obvious reasons]) so that the class can use the material as a study tool.
          </p>
          <p>
           	Your grade will reflect both the effort that you put in, as well as the usefulness of your study guide. Creative study guides will be graded as  ++ (100%), + (90%),  (80%), -(70%), -- (50%), or 0%. 
          </p>
       </li>

       <li>
          <title>3 Minute Thesis</title>
          <p>
            The 3 Minute Thesis (3MT) is a recent phenomenon where students summarize the entirety of their thesis work into the span of three minutes. This may sound like a very easy task, but you must fully understand the background, importance, and molecular biology in order to fully convey a topic in 3 minutes! 
          </p>
          <p>
           	The goal of this project is twofold:
          </p>
          <p>
            Work on succinct, oral scientific communication and public speaking 
          </p>
          <p>
            Learn to apply the information that we learned this semester to new molecules / pathways
          </p>
          <p>
             	Your topic <em>must focus on the molecular biology</em> of something that we have not covered in this course.
          </p>
          <p>
            You will have exactly <em>3 minutes</em> and <em>1 static slide</em> to present your topic.
          </p>
          <p>
            We will use one lab period to practice 3MT presentations
          </p>
       </li>

       <li>
          <title>Participation</title>
          <p>
             	There will be <em>no rounding</em> in this course
          </p>
          <p>
             	Students may earn up to 2 bonus points for participation
          </p>
          <p>
             	A student aiming to receive the full 2 points for participation should anticipate coming to class every day, responding to multiple questions daily, regularly coming to office hours or emailing me, etc. Students who do these activities occasionally will receive proportionally fewer of these possible two bonus points.
          </p>
          <p>
             	Please note that I will <em>not</em> be <em>'bumping'</em> grades if you are on the cusp of a higher letter grade. The participation points are meant to be a fair way to raise the grades of those students who worked hard and engaged in the class.
          </p>
       </li>

        </dl>
      </p>
     </paragraphs>
    
  </subsection>







   <!-- Other subsections for larger dividers -->
  <subsection xml:id="sec-schedule">
    <paragraphs>
      <title>Assignments and Grades</title>
      <p>
        <dl>
              
       <li>
          <title>Exams</title>
          <p>
              There will be 3 semester exams, all on Fridays
          </p>
          <p>
            October 17th - Exam 1
          </p>
          <p>
            November 7th - Exam 2
          </p>
          <p>
            December 5th - Exam 3
          </p>
       </li>

       <li>
          <title>Final Exam</title>
          <p>
              There will be 1, cumulative final exam
          </p>
          <p>
            December 17th - Final Exam
          </p>
          <p>
            The final exam will be at 11:30 am
          </p>
       </li>

       <li>
          <title>Structure Quiz</title>
          <p>
            There will be 1 structure quiz this semester
          </p>
          <p>
            September 26th - Structure Quiz
          </p>
       </li>

       <li>
          <title>Laboratory Assignments</title>
          <p>
            There will be multiple laboratory assignments this semester. All lab assignments are outlined in more detail in the lab syllabus
          </p>
       </li>

       <li>
          <title>Problem Sets</title>
          <p>
            There will be 14 problem sets this semester, all due on Thursdays at 11:30am. The final day to submit all problem sets is the day before the exam that that problem covers the content for 
          </p>
          <p>
            September 11th - Problem Set 1
          </p>
          <p>
            September 18th - Problem Set 2
          </p>
          <p>
            September 25th - Problem Set 3
          </p>
          <p>
            October 2nd - Problem Set 4
          </p>
          <p>
            October 9th - Problem Set 5
